Database information:¶

The Global Terrorism Database (GTD) is an open-source database including information on terrorist events around the world from 1970 through 2017 (with additional annual updates planned). Unlike many other event databases, the GTD includes systematic data on domestic as well as transnational and international terrorist incidents that have occurred date and location of the incident, the weapons used and nature of the target, the number of casualties, and--when identifiable--the group or individual responsible. The National Consortium for the Study of Terrorism and Responses to Terrorism (START) makes the GTD available via this online interface in an effort to increase understanding of terrorist violence so that it can be more readily studied and defeated.

Characteristics of the GTD:¶

• Contains information on over 180,000 terrorist attacks.

• Currently the most comprehensive unclassified database on terrorist attacks in the world.

• Includes information on more than 88,000 bombings, 19,000 assassinations, and 11,000 kidnappings since 1970.

• Includes information on at least 45 variables for each case, with more recent incidents including information on more than 120 variables.

Note: In the GTD data, the data for the year 1993 is missing and we have decided to ignore this as it won’t be having much impact on the overall data analysis.

[1] The GTD data can be downloaded from https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd in .xlsx form and it has been converted to .csv after downloading.

[2] Details about the variables and their meanings can be found and downloaded from the data dictionary (GTD Code Book) which is available at http://start.umd.edu/gtd/downloads/Codebook.pdf

Objectives¶

1. Cleaning and Preparing the data for Analysis

• Identify the significant variable groups contributing to our analysis – events(attacks) details like location(country, region, city, latitude, longitude), when it happened(year, month), criteria, attack type, target type, terrorist group, weapon type used for the attack, number of kills, injured, property loss value, hostage taken or not.

• Renaming the columns for analysis convenience.

• Identify the string type columns with white spaces and deleting them from analysis.

• Find the NaN cells in the dataset and replacing with 0’s or 1’s or particular text corresponding to the column type.

• Identify the observations which have data with special characters like series of “ . ”, “ – “ etc and replacing them with “Unknown”.

• Resetting the index.

2. Study the following trends

• Number of attacks over the years

• Number of people killed over the years due to terrorist attacks

• Regions affected by terrorists attacks over the years

• Number of failed attacks (zero number of people killed is the criteria)

• Property loss over the years (not accounting inflation)

• Are there any changes in type of attack, target type over the years

• How lethal are the attacks over the years?

3. Identify the top deadliest terrorist groups (more killings and attacks) in each decade.

• Spread of each group from their inception

• How long does an average terrorist group be active?

4. Identify the top 10 countries experiencing terrorist attacks after 2000 and analyze the following parameters for each country

• Which terrorist groups are dominant in each of the country?

• Property value loss

• Number of people killed

• Attack type, Target types, Weapon type

• Find the factors or real life events contributing to these attacks.

5. Study and research in detail the reasons for increase in attacks in the year 2014 globally.

Variables of Significance:¶

The dataset has 181691 records with 135 columns. We have chosen the variables of significance by choosing a subset of all the variables for analyzing the GTD Data. They are iyear, imonth, extended, country_txt, region_txt, provstate, city, latitude, longitude, crit1, crit2, multiple, success, suicide, attacktype1_txt, targtype1_txt, gname, claimed, weaptype1_txt, nkill, nkillus, nkillter, nwound, nwoundus, nwoundte, property, propextent_txt

(5) In the numerical columns like crit1, claimed etc, we found that there are some NaNs. We don't want any NaNs as they automatically convert the column to dtype=float. So we tried to clean them by using fillna()

In [5]:
# Deal with unknowns in numeric columns
numerical_unknowns = ['Latitude', 'Longitude','Year']
float_cols = [c for c in df.select_dtypes(include=[float]).columns.tolist() if c not in numerical_unknowns]
# We don't want any NaNs as they automatically convert the column to dtype=float
# Convert the unknowns into negative numbers, say -9
df[float_cols] = df[float_cols].fillna(0).astype(int)
df[float_cols] = df[float_cols].mask(df[float_cols] < 0, 0)
df.head(5)

Analysis and Visualizations:¶

We have tried to explore the cleaned dataset and have come-up with the following analysis and visualizations.

1) Number of Civilians killed every year

In [8]:
import seaborn as sns 
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
df['Number_of_killed'].fillna(0)
no_of_killed_civilians = df.groupby('Year')['Number_of_killed'].sum()
plt.subplots(figsize=(15,10))
pt1 = sns.barplot(no_of_killed_civilians.index,no_of_killed_civilians,color='royalblue')
pt1.set_xlabel("Year")
pt1.set_ylabel("Number of killed_civilians")
pt1.set_xticklabels(no_of_killed_civilians.index,rotation=90)
plt.show()

From the above visualization we can see that over the years, in the year 2014, 100 countries experienced the attacks and 44,490 people killed. This shows us that the worst year for terrorism over the past couple of decades is 2014.

Also, we can see that this sharp rise in the terrorism in the year 2014 could have given rise to many anti-terrorism measures by the Governments of many countries of the world, thus creating a decline in the impact of terrorism in the consequent years 2015, 2016 and 2017. Where, the impact in 2017 has reduced to almost half of the impact which was in the year 2014.

Similar kind of stories indicating that 2014 was the year where terrorism was at its peak point can be interpreted from the visualizations 2,3 and 4.

#Identifying the dangerous terrorist groups based on the number of attacks and number of people killed

df = df[~df['gname'].isin(['Unknown'])]
df13 = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(['gname'])['Number_of_killed'].agg(['sum','count']))
df13.reset_index(level=0,inplace=True)

df13 = df13.rename(columns={'sum':'Number of people killed'})
df13 = df13.rename(columns={'count':'Number of attacks'})

df13 = df13.astype({"Number of people killed": int})
df13.reset_index(level=0,inplace=True,drop=True)

Function which gives out the visualizations of the number of attacks done by a particular terrorist group over a range of years

In [14]:
# Number of attacks done by a particular terrorist group over a range of years 
def attacks_per_month(df9,gname,year):
    data = df9[(df9['gname']==gname) & (df9['Year']==year)]
    attacks_month = data.groupby(['Month_of_attack'])['Number_of_killed'].sum()
    plot2 = sns.barplot(attacks_month.index ,attacks_month,color='royalblue')
    plot2.set_xlabel('Months')
    plot2.set_ylabel('Number of Attacks')
    plot2.set_title(gname + " in "+str(year))
    plt.show()

From the Visualizations 14,15,16 and 17, we can see that terrorism in the form of bombing and armed assaults has been used to affect the civilians and thereby impact the government in most of the developing countries like India, Afghanistan etc.

Whereas, terrorism has been used in the form of assasination of popular persons or leaders in developed countries like United Kingdom.

#df = df[~df['gname'].isin(['Unknown'])]
#df_deadliest = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(['Year'])['Number_of_killed'].agg(['sum','count']))

def attack_stats(df9,country):
    data = df9[(df9['Country']==country)]
    data = data[~data['gname'].isin(['Unknown'])]
    terr_groups1 = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby(['gname'])['Number_of_killed'].agg(['sum','count']))
    terr_groups = pd.DataFrame(data.groupby(['gname'])['Number_of_killed'].count())
    #display(terr_groups)
    terr_groups = terr_groups.rename(columns={'Number_of_killed':'Number of attacks'})
    terr_groups.sort_values(by=['Number of attacks'],ascending=False,inplace=True)
    terr_groups1 = terr_groups1.rename(columns={'sum':'Number of people killed'})
    terr_groups1 = terr_groups1.rename(columns={'count':'Number of attacks'})
    terr_groups1 = terr_groups1.astype({"Number of people killed": int})
    plt.plot(terr_groups1['Number of people killed'],terr_groups1['Number of attacks'],'k.')
    plt.xlabel('Number of people killed')
    plt.ylabel('Number of attacks')
    plt.title('Correlation = %.4f' % terr_groups1['Number of people killed'].corr(terr_groups1['Number of attacks']));
    #terr_groups['Ratio'] = (terr_groups['Number of people killed']/(terr_groups['Number of attacks']))
    #terr_groups = terr_groups.sort_values(by=['Ratio'], ascending = False)

    #plot2.set_xlabel('Months')
    #plot2.set_ylabel('Number of Attacks')
    #plot2.set_title(gname + " in "+str(year))
    #plt.show()
    df1 = df9[(df9['Country']==country)]
    df1=df1[df1['property']==1]

#attack_on_property.sort_values(by=['Count of attacks'],ascending=False,inplace=True)
#display(attack_on_property)
    attack_on_property_country.plot(kind='bar',stacked=True,figsize=(15,15),width=0.7,colormap=cmap1)
    df1 = df9[(df9['Country']==country)]
    df1=df1[df1['Year'].isin({"2006","2007","2008","2009","2010","2011","2012","2013","2014","2015","2016","2017"})]

attack_stats(df,"India")

The function attack_stats gives us the statistics regarding:

1) The visualization between the number of people killed and the number of attacks

2) Extent of property damage over the past decade

3) Number of killed over the past decade

4) Type of target over the past decade

5) Type of attack over the past decade

6) Type of weapon over the past decade

All these stats can be specifically obtained for any country present in our dataset by passing the country name to the attack_stats function.
